<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-12-11T04:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-12-11T04:00:00-05:00" n="72" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d72">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">330/12–1151: Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Greece</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Peurifoy</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#left">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                                    <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">priority</hi>
                                </seg>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Athens</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-12-11T11:00:00+02:00">December 11, 1951—11 a.m.</date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>2700. This morning Plastiras sent Moatsis, chief of <gloss target="#t_PriMin1">PriMin</gloss>’s polit bureau, to tell me
                                that if Greece’s candidacy for <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> is
                                proving at all embarrassing for us in our relations with UK or
                                others <gloss target="#t_PriMin1">PriMin</gloss> wld immed issue
                                orders withdrawing Greece from race.</p>
                            <p>Moatsis emphasized Plastiras’ intense desire for complete cooperation
                                with us particularly in foreign affairs. He added that <gloss target="#t_PriMin1">PriMin</gloss> had been intensely irritated
                                by Politis’ activities in early <gloss target="#t_GA1">GA</gloss>
                                meetings, and wished us to know that he disapproved of any
                                maneuvering by Grk rep which wld not be wholly in accord with Amer
                                wishes.</p>
                            <pb facs="0144" n="122" xml:id="pg_122"/>
                            <p>Wld appreciate immed telegraphic advice so that I may answer
                                    Plastiras.<note n="1" xml:id="d72fn1">In telegram 2804, December
                                    11, 7:36 p. m. (repeated for information to Paris as <gloss target="#t_Gadel2">Gadel</gloss> 419) the Department
                                    responded: “Inform Plastiras that Greek candidacy not proving
                                    embarrassing to U.S. from standpoint our relations with U.K. and
                                    that U.S. intends vote for Greece during balloting scheduled
                                    December 13.” (330/12–1151)</note>
                            </p>
                            <p>Sent priority <gloss target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss> 2700; rptd info
                                Paris 72 for <gloss target="#t_USDel1">USDel</gloss>.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Peurifoy</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>